The result of the operation depends on the underlying C++ implementation and default setting.

To be certain at all the times what is our rounding, we can explicitly set the `std::fesetround(FE_TONEAREST);` when entering the C++ context and restore the previous mode if is not set to FE_TONEAREST.

```
save_rint_setting = std::fegetround();
std::fesetround(FE_TONEAREST);
std::rint(value);
std::fesetround(save_rint_setting);
```

### Default settings
- The gnu library is set to `FE_TONEAREST` by default.
  http://www.gnu.org/software/libc/manual/html_node/Rounding.html
- The cudnn library _seems_ to use a logic like TONEAREST http://docs.nvidia.com/cuda/cuda-c-programming-guide/index.html#standard-functions but is not something explicitly set.
  I can just just ignore this entire issue and say in the description that does rounding 'to nearest'.
